---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { project, data, citations, limitations } from '../lib/canonical.ts';
---
<Base
  title={`About — ${project.name}`}
  description="How this project was built, what the data can and can't tell you, and how to cite it."
  ogImage="/og/about.png"
  pathname="/about/"
>
  <Nav />

  <main id="main">
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-5 sm:px-8 pt-12 sm:pt-20 pb-16">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-4">About this project</p>
    <h1 class="h-display mb-6">A field guide to the emotional shape of meditation communities online.</h1>

    <div class="prose-editorial">
      <p>
        {project.name} is a visual analysis of {data.post_count_canonical.toLocaleString()} r/meditation
        posts and comments from {data.date_range_human}. It maps the emotional vocabulary the community
        actually uses, the response patterns between posters and commenters, the mood weather across
        topics over six quarters, and the way theme connections drift quarter by quarter.
      </p>
      <p>
        The finding is summarized in one line: <strong>the dominant emotional register on r/meditation
        isn't peace, it's struggle wrapped around curiosity</strong>. Joy ranks 25th of 28 emotions in
        the GoEmotions classification. Amusement is dead last. The vocabulary that dominates is
        <em>"I'm trying again."</em>
      </p>
      <p>
        Two long-form essays unpack the findings:
        <a href={data.subreddit ? "https://minyansh.substack.com/p/what-48000-reddit-posts-on-meditation" : "#"}>
          What 3,000 Reddit posts on meditation actually sound like</a> (the thesis essay) and
        <a href="https://minyansh.substack.com/p/the-emotion-map-of-meditation-online">
          Meditation communities are not as calm as they look</a> (the response-pattern essay).
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="h-section mt-16 mb-6" id="methodology">Methodology.</h2>
    <div class="prose-editorial">
      <p>
        The corpus is <strong>{data.post_count_canonical.toLocaleString()} posts and comments</strong>
        from <a href={`https://www.reddit.com/${data.subreddit}/`} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{data.subreddit}</a>,
        spanning {data.date_range_human}. Posts without at least one comment were filtered out, since
        the response-pattern analysis depends on comment-side data; the pre-filter total was 2,977.
        The canonical figure used on every public surface is <strong>{data.post_count_canonical.toLocaleString()}</strong>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each post and comment is classified by Google Research's <strong>GoEmotions</strong> model
        (Demszky et al. 2020), which scores text against a 27-emotion taxonomy plus neutral. Embeddings
        from the classifier are projected to two dimensions via UMAP (McInnes et al. 2018) and clustered
        with a Gaussian Mixture Model into the five emotional archetypes shown on the
        <a href="/explore/emotion-pulse/">Emotion Pulse</a> page. Topic clusters were derived separately
        and labeled by hand into seven theme families: Anxiety &amp; Mental Health, Awareness, Buddhism &amp;
        Spirituality, Concentration &amp; Flow, Meditation &amp; Mindfulness, Practice/Retreat/Meta, and
        Self-Regulation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Source code, processed parquet artifacts, and the analysis scripts live in
        <a href={project.github} target="_blank" rel="noopener">the GitHub repository</a>. The dataset
        will be published on HuggingFace with a stable DOI; that's the citable artifact.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="h-section mt-16 mb-6" id="limitations">Limitations — what this can and can't tell you.</h2>
    <div class="prose-editorial">
      <p>This analysis has real limits. They aren't a defect, they're the shape of the work:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-3 my-6">
        {limitations.map((l) => <li>{l}</li>)}
      </ul>
      <p>
        The most consequential of these is the <strong>model circularity</strong>. GoEmotions was
        trained on Reddit comments. Applying it to r/meditation Reddit posts means part of what we
        see is what Reddit emotion looks like in general, not specifically what meditation talk looks
        like. The thesis ("struggle wrapped around curiosity") is robust to this — both struggle
        words and curiosity words are well-distributed in the GoEmotions training set — but specific
        rankings (e.g. "joy ranks 25th of 28") should be read as <em>relative within this corpus</em>,
        not as a universal claim about meditation.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="h-section mt-16 mb-6" id="ethics">Ethics &amp; takedowns.</h2>
    <div class="prose-editorial">
      <p>
        Reddit posts are public, but using them at scale for a public visualization requires care.
        Quotes shown in tooltips and essays are <strong>paraphrased, not verbatim</strong>; specific
        usernames, post URLs, and identifying details are not surfaced. If you find yourself in this
        data and would like your post excluded, email
        <a href={`mailto:${project.takedown}`}>{project.takedown}</a> with a link to the post and
        we'll remove it from the next data refresh.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="h-section mt-16 mb-6" id="cite">Cite this work.</h2>
    <div class="prose-editorial">
      <p>If you reference {project.name} in research or writing:</p>
      <pre class="bg-[var(--color-surface)] border border-[var(--color-hairline)] rounded-lg p-4 text-xs sm:text-sm overflow-x-auto"><code>{`Shi, M. (2026). MindSpace OS: An emotion map of online meditation
  discourse from r/meditation, 2024–2025. ${project.domain}`}</code></pre>
      <p class="mt-6">It also rests on these prior works:</p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 mt-4 text-sm">
        {citations.map((c) => (
          <li>
            <strong>{c.label}</strong> — {c.authors} ({c.year}). <em>{c.title}.</em>
            {c.venue && <span> {c.venue}.</span>}
            {c.arxiv && <span> arXiv:<a href={c.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{c.arxiv}</a>.</span>}
            {c.huggingface && <span> <a href={c.huggingface} target="_blank" rel="noopener">HuggingFace</a>.</span>}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2 class="h-section mt-16 mb-6">Built by.</h2>
    <div class="prose-editorial">
      <p>
        MindSpace OS is built by <a href={project.linkedin} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Minyan Shi</a>
        at MinyanLabs. Subscribe to the <a href={project.substack_pub} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        Substack</a> for the next essay. Reach out at
        <a href={`mailto:${project.contact}`}>{project.contact}</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Base>
